article.description:
Ray Allen scored a season-high 40 points and Predrag Drobnjak added
19 as the Sonics matched their longest winning streak of the
season with a 109-101 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers.
article.headline: Sonics 4-1 since Allen entered their lineup
article.linkText: Allen's season-high 40 points sends Sonics past Clips
article.story:
LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Ray Allen has become the perfect fit for the Seattle SuperSonics.
Allen

Allen scored a season-high 40 points Saturday night as the Sonics ended a six-game road losing streak with a 109-101 victory over the Los Angeles Clippers. "Ray is a very confident and mature player. He knows his game, and his ability to create opportunities for others is great,'' Seattle coach Nate McMillan said. "He makes decisions like a point guard and he runs the whole floor.'' Seattle is 4-1 with Allen in the lineup. The three-time All-Star is averaging 27.8 points, 7.8 assists and 7.4 rebounds in five games since being acquired in a multi-player deal that sent Gary Payton to Milwaukee. "The guys and the coaching staff have done a great job of allowing me to prosper in this system,'' Allen said. "Every time down the floor, Brent Barry is telling me what the play is and where I need to go. We're playing well together, passing the ball and getting good shots.'' Fresh off a 107-90 home victory over the defending champion Los Angeles Lakers the previous night, Seattle extended its winning streak to four games with help from Predrag Drobnjak's 19 points and seven rebounds. The win, coupled with Phoenix's loss to New Orleans, pulled the Sonics within 2½ games of the Suns for the eighth and final Western Conference playoff spot. "They're running things a lot better right now,'' Clippers swingman Melvin Ely said. "Ray fits in perfectly with their scheme. He doesn't do anything out of character. He helps his team in every aspect, so he's a great addition to their team.'' Corey Maggette scored 17 points for the Clippers, who have lost five straight and 14 of 17. Leading scorer Elton Brand missed his third straight game because of a stress fracture above his left ankle -- an injury that originally was diagnosed as a bruise. For an eight-minute span in the fourth quarter, the Clippers never trailed by more than 11 points or fewer than nine until Brent Barry made a 3-pointer from the right corner and Allen hit two free throws to give Seattle a 102-88 lead with 2½ minutes to play. Los Angeles responded with a 11-2 run -- including a 22-footer and a 3-pointer by Quentin Richardson -- which sliced the deficit to 104-99 and forced the Sonics to call a timeout with 45.6 seconds left. But the Clippers got no closer. "I'm a competitor. I hate to lose, and it gets more and more frustrating every time we have a chance to win games and don't,'' Richardson said. Clippers backup center Sean Rooks displayed his frustration with 3:58 left in the third quarter and the Clippers trailing 68-59. He had just made a layup and thought he was fouled, but didn't get the call and was ejected after arguing with referee Bob Delaney. Allen sank both free throws following the double technicals against Rooks, triggering an 11-3 spurt that extended Seattle's margin to 79-62 with 1:42 left in the third. He capped the rally with a 19-footer and a 3-pointer 26 seconds apart. The Sonics led 56-52 at halftime, powered by Allen's 20 points. Vladimir Radmanovic hit a 3-pointer to give the Sonics a 26-25 lead with 58 seconds left in the first quarter. Seattle held the lead the rest of the way, building an eight-point advantage on Jerome James' short hook shot with 7:15 left in the half. "We didn't establish a tone to the defense in the first half,'' McMillan said. "In the second half, we played better defense and focused on containing those guys.''

Game notes
The Sonics had lost 15 straight games in which they have allowed at least 100 points, including 13 this season. This was the first time they allowed at least 100 points in a win since last Apr. 8 -- against the Clippers at KeyArena. ... Seattle beat the Clippers for the 40th time in the last 46 meetings between the teams. ... The Sonics shot 54.8 from the field, ending a streak of 32 games in which they failed to shoot better than 50 percent. ... Since moving to Staples Center four seasons ago, the Clippers have been drawing the kind of celebrities that wouldn't have been caught dead in the L.A. Sports Arena. Exhibit A: actress Jane Seymour, in a front-row seat at midcourt. ... Allen entered with the league's third-best free throw percentage at .913, trailing only Allen Houston and Steve Nash. He was 11-for-12 against the Clippers.
